Dialogue: 0,0:00:01.55,0:00:07.37,Default,,0,0,0,,The most precious moment in life is the time of decision.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:07.37,0:00:19.93,Default,,0,0,0,,The Pacific War taught us the preciousness of peace, but it also leaves us with many lessons to live.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:24.27,0:00:32.65,Default,,0,0,0,,Ketsudan (decision)
Dialogue: 0,0:00:34.27,0:00:49.13,Default,,0,0,0,,Use your wisdom Use your head Keep thinking it you're a man
Dialogue: 0,0:00:49.13,0:00:58.20,Default,,0,0,0,,Whether you cry or laugh, it depends on your decision
Dialogue: 0,0:00:58.20,0:01:06.06,Default,,0,0,0,,Don't be arrogant even if you win Don't cry even if you lose
Dialogue: 0,0:01:06.06,0:01:13.58,Default,,0,0,0,,Man does not show tears
Dialogue: 0,0:01:28.58,0:01:35.24,Default,,0,0,0,,Tatsunoko Production
Dialogue: 0,0:01:41.39,0:01:54.94,Default,,0,0,0,,In April 1943, with the Americans having captured Guadalcanal the Japanese were fiercely defending against them advancing along the Solomon Islands.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:56.08,0:02:05.60,Default,,0,0,0,,lsoroku Yamamoto, Commander-in-Chief of the Allied Fleet, flew from the base on Truck Island to Rabaul on the front line for a front-line inspection.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:06.50,0:02:11.12,Default,,0,0,0,,> Attention. Salute.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:26.63,0:02:30.46,Default,,0,0,0,,> You see. It's a Japanese radio message.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:33.46,0:02:37.94,Default,,0,0,0,,> The Combat Intelligence Department, which belongs to the United States Pacific Fleet Command in Hawaii,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:37.94,0:02:44.15,Default,,0,0,0,,is located in a top secret basement that can only be used by the cryptanalysis team.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:50.25,0:02:57.36,Default,,0,0,0,,All the radio messages of the Japanese Navy received from various parts of the South Pacific are collected here,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:57.36,0:03:06.60,Default,,0,0,0,,and this electric cryptanalyzer was devised and developed by Major Thomas Dyer, a leading expert in cryptographic analysis in the US.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:06.60,0:03:13.84,Default,,0,0,0,,It had been enhanced to the point where it could almost decipher the Japanese Navy's encrypted messages.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:19.56,0:03:26.43,Default,,0,0,0,,> Hey, take a look. > What is this? It's not like a Japanese sentence.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:28.70,0:03:30.77,Default,,0,0,0,,> I wonder if the machine broke.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:32.05,0:03:38.25,Default,,0,0,0,,> Look at this. >I don't know. Call Major Dier right away. It's urgent.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:41.22,0:03:48.18,Default,,0,0,0,,Operation Vengeance (Episode 18)
Dialogue: 0,0:04:02.81,0:04:04.84,Default,,0,0,0,,> Major Dier.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:07.56,0:04:11.94,Default,,0,0,0,,> It is not a mechanical failure. The code of the Japanese Navy has changed.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:12.60,0:04:15.63,Default,,0,0,0,,> Has it changed completely? > I don't know.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:16.22,0:04:19.46,Default,,0,0,0,,> If so, this machine is no longer useful.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:20.05,0:04:24.63,Default,,0,0,0,,> We have to make a new decipherer. How many months will that take?
Dialogue: 0,0:04:24.94,0:04:33.32,Default,,0,0,0,,> It takes half a year. However, cryptography does not always change completely. Anyway, break this code.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:33.32,0:04:34.53,Default,,0,0,0,,> Yes
Dialogue: 0,0:04:35.25,0:04:41.08,Default,,0,0,0,,> Even if you stay up all night, you must break this code. > Yes
Dialogue: 0,0:05:03.53,0:05:10.22,Default,,0,0,0,,> How much can the Navy do if it comes to war with the United States and Britain?
Dialogue: 0,0:05:10.22,0:05:17.63,Default,,0,0,0,,> I am a soldier. If I am told to do it, let's do it. For half a year or a year, we can plan as much as I want.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:17.63,0:05:21.87,Default,,0,0,0,,However, we cannot guarantee it after that.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:25.77,0:05:32.67,Default,,0,0,0,,> Was it a dream? That year is over.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:45.01,0:05:48.80,Default,,0,0,0,,> Who is it? I am sorry.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:49.91,0:05:55.05,Default,,0,0,0,,> I woke up after dreaming. I want to go to the beach, is that okay?
Dialogue: 0,0:05:55.05,0:05:56.70,Default,,0,0,0,,> Yes. I will be with you.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:15.05,0:06:20.49,Default,,0,0,0,,> Chief, this one. > No, this feels better.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:21.74,0:06:28.49,Default,,0,0,0,,> I don't think it's the sea where the war is going on. Have you been working in Rabaul all the time?
Dialogue: 0,0:06:28.94,0:06:34.77,Default,,0,0,0,,> No. I was in Bougainville three months ago. > Oh. It's the front line.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:35.60,0:06:41.25,Default,,0,0,0,,> How was it, over there? > Yes. The Bougainville Reserves are unfortunately poor.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:41.77,0:06:45.01,Default,,0,0,0,,> Is Rabaul any good? > Yes
Dialogue: 0,0:06:45.15,0:06:50.49,Default,,0,0,0,,> Thanks to being in Rabaul, I can see the Commander-in-Chief of the Allied Fleet in this way.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:52.84,0:06:55.08,Default,,0,0,0,,> Just relax. > Yes
Dialogue: 0,0:06:55.08,0:06:58.08,Default,,0,0,0,,> Are you glad I come to Rabaul so much?
Dialogue: 0,0:06:59.12,0:07:04.94,Default,,0,0,0,,> Yes. The Chief is the guardian deity of the Imperial Japanese Navy. You are a god.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:05.74,0:07:11.60,Default,,0,0,0,,> You exaggerate. I also drink alcohol and like gambling. Is there such a god?
Dialogue: 0,0:07:12.08,0:07:23.08,Default,,0,0,0,,> That's why you're God. You are right next to us. I feel sorry for the people in Bougainville because they can't worship God directly.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:28.29,0:07:31.25,Default,,0,0,0,,> Bougainville.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:41.53,0:07:44.91,Default,,0,0,0,,> How do you feel about carrying God?
Dialogue: 0,0:07:44.91,0:07:48.39,Default,,0,0,0,,> I will have to pay for it. I'm happy.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:05.29,0:08:07.94,Default,,0,0,0,,> I understand. I solved it.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:11.91,0:08:16.53,Default,,0,0,0,,> We don't have to stay up all night anymore. The code was broken.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:20.77,0:08:28.25,Default,,0,0,0,,> The Japanese Navy did not change the code. They just changed the random number table a little. All we have to do is tell that to the machine.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:28.25,0:08:31.32,Default,,0,0,0,,> Then, that decryption machine can be used? > Of course.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:31.32,0:08:34.56,Default,,0,0,0,,> I came to Rabaul. > I have to go to Bougainville.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:34.56,0:08:43.77,Default,,0,0,0,,> Bougainville is 500kms from here. It's dangerous. > The air superiority of this area is in our hands so far. It's okay.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:44.12,0:08:50.22,Default,,0,0,0,,> However, the Japanese do not have complete air superiority. I don't know when the enemy planes will appear.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:50.91,0:08:57.46,Default,,0,0,0,,> Excuse me, but I think that the Commander-in-Chief should never leave the safe area.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:57.46,0:09:01.29,Default,,0,0,0,,> When the Chief does that, then that will be when the Imperial Japanese Navy is destroyed.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:01.29,0:09:07.80,Default,,0,0,0,,> This theory is exactly what you guys say. But I want to go.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:07.81,0:09:11.18,Default,,0,0,0,,Yamamoto came all the way to Rabaul, but was it useful?
Dialogue: 0,0:09:11.19,0:09:22.18,Default,,0,0,0,,I can only make the soldiers guarding small islands around the Pacific think, "Hey, Yamamoto is here, lets do it well."
Dialogue: 0,0:09:22.19,0:09:29.22,Default,,0,0,0,,Yamamoto shows his face here, then the front line for the Japanese forces isn't so terrifying. I want them to think so.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:29.22,0:09:31.98,Default,,0,0,0,,> Chief. I understand that.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:33.50,0:09:39.98,Default,,0,0,0,,> Come out, come out. Oh my goodness!
Dialogue: 0,0:09:50.32,0:09:55.80,Default,,0,0,0,,> It's big news. Connect to Lieutenant Colonel Layton. It's urgent.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:58.67,0:10:00.80,Default,,0,0,0,,> Lieutenant Colonel Layton enter.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:23.56,0:10:27.01,Default,,0,0,0,,> Could Yamamoto make such a stupid mistake?
Dialogue: 0,0:10:28.01,0:10:30.22,Default,,0,0,0,,> Even if it’s a trap, it’s too good.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:33.67,0:10:36.05,Default,,0,0,0,,> Just listen as you are.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:36.91,0:10:44.53,Default,,0,0,0,,Who is the one who wrote such a message? Is there anyone who can describe the actions of the Commander-in-Chief of the Allied Fleet in such detail?
Dialogue: 0,0:10:45.32,0:10:52.18,Default,,0,0,0,,It's like sending an invitation to the enemy, Let the Chief know that I have flown from Bougainville.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:55.94,0:11:02.84,Default,,0,0,0,,> Chief. Bougainville is absolutely okay as long as it is defended by me. Please retrain from visiting.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:03.22,0:11:06.74,Default,,0,0,0,,> It doesn't mean that I'll show up because I can't leave it to you
Dialogue: 0,0:11:06.74,0:11:11.77,Default,,0,0,0,,> I understand, but why did you lay out that detailed schedule of the Chief's inspection?
Dialogue: 0,0:11:11.77,0:11:15.05,Default,,0,0,0,,What it this message is intercepted by the US?
Dialogue: 0,0:11:15.43,0:11:19.46,Default,,0,0,0,,> Our code may have been broken, or they may not have been able to.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:19.46,0:11:26.49,Default,,0,0,0,,It is usually undecipherable. I cannot lose great joy in the unlikely event.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:38.25,0:11:43.18,Default,,0,0,0,,> Sir, can you believe this Japanese message?
Dialogue: 0,0:11:43.60,0:11:48.91,Default,,0,0,0,,This is the responsibility of Admiral Nimitz, Commander-in-Chief of the United States Pacific Fleet.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:49.70,0:11:51.43,Default,,0,0,0,,> Come in.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:53.50,0:11:55.80,Default,,0,0,0,,> This is a top secret message from Dutch Harbor in Alaska.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:00.19,0:12:01.39,Default,,0,0,0,,> Let's read it.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:01.39,0:12:11.53,Default,,0,0,0,,> On April 18th, Commander-in-Chief of the Allied Fleet Yamamoto will visit the island on the front line.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:11.53,0:12:22.87,Default,,0,0,0,,6am. This must be Rabaul’s Japanese time. Depart Rabaul with six escort aircraft Zero fighters. 8am. Arrive at Bougainville.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:24.36,0:12:27.63,Default,,0,0,0,,> It matches exactly with the message from the Japanese from Hawaii.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:27.63,0:12:34.43,Default,,0,0,0,,We also caught this encrypted message in Alaska. What was their intention in sending such a strong radio wave?
Dialogue: 0,0:12:35.53,0:12:43.63,Default,,0,0,0,,Is it a trap? > No, it's the result of confidence that the US can't break their code.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:54.74,0:13:03.12,Default,,0,0,0,,> We were given very difficult homework. You already have the data that I have handed out. Ask questions.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:03.12,0:13:07.94,Default,,0,0,0,,> There are few escort planes for Mr. Yamamoto, but there are also Zero fighters in Bougainville.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:08.56,0:13:15.63,Default,,0,0,0,,> We only have P-38s. No matter how close we are to Yamamoto, we can't fly to Bougainville.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:15.91,0:13:23.60,Default,,0,0,0,,> Let me answer. Bougainville certainly has Zero fighters, So hit Mr. Yamamoto before he lands on Bougainville.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:24.08,0:13:27.56,Default,,0,0,0,,Major Mitchell, it's time to explain your plan.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:27.56,0:13:34.53,Default,,0,0,0,,> If I can solve this homework, I will be the commander. So here is my answer.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:34.98,0:13:39.15,Default,,0,0,0,,The target is Bougainville, about 600kms from our base.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:39.15,0:13:46.01,Default,,0,0,0,,The first thing is how to fly so that the enemy does not see us coming. So, we fly at a low altitude just above the sea.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:46.01,0:13:52.12,Default,,0,0,0,,> If Yamamoto, our key objective, does not fly as planned, wouldn't it be possible to pass each other in the vast Pacific Ocean?
Dialogue: 0,0:13:52.56,0:13:58.39,Default,,0,0,0,,> That's right. That is the most difficult point. The distance from here to Bougainville is 600kms.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:58.39,0:14:05.12,Default,,0,0,0,,500kms from Rabaul, where Mr. Yamamoto is, to Bougainville. There is a difference of 100kms.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:06.19,0:14:14.53,Default,,0,0,0,,There is only one place in the South Pacific where the two lines meet most effectively. How to find that one point.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:14.94,0:14:17.49,Default,,0,0,0,,> What is your answer? > There is only one.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:18.53,0:14:26.70,Default,,0,0,0,,> Start one hour before Mr. Yamamoto and ambush him on the way. Yamamoto is a man who always keeps his promises.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:26.70,0:14:31.08,Default,,0,0,0,,> Does he really keep your promises? The attack on Pearl Harbor was a surprise.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:31.08,0:14:35.29,Default,,0,0,0,,> No, that was a strategy to attack after the declaration of war.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:35.84,0:14:39.98,Default,,0,0,0,,At that time, the people at the Japanese embassy In Washington made a mistake and the time was off.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:40.60,0:14:44.63,Default,,0,0,0,,Yamamoto struck Pearl Harbor at the promised time without knowing war had not been declared.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:45.46,0:14:47.77,Default,,0,0,0,,> Make a note of the final decision.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:47.77,0:14:57.63,Default,,0,0,0,,First proceed 133kms, 265 degrees directional. Speed 360kms, flight time 55 minutes, and so on.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:58.53,0:15:11.70,Default,,0,0,0,,Second, l44kms, 240 degrees orientation, 27 minutes. Third, 200kms, 305 degrees orientation, 38 minutes.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:13.25,0:15:17.39,Default,,0,0,0,,If all goes well, we will definitely hit the enemy before 8 o'clock. That's all.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:17.39,0:15:27.22,Default,,0,0,0,,> It's a wonderful answer to your homework. But Layton, no country has killed an enemy Commander-In-Chief like this during the war in World-War I.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:27.22,0:15:32.15,Default,,0,0,0,,> President. Yamamoto is was the planner for the undeclared attack on Pearl Harbor.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:32.15,0:15:39.56,Default,,0,0,0,,Don't worry. This is fair. Please make a decision. There are only two days left.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:39.56,0:15:44.01,Default,,0,0,0,,> However, Yamamoto is a regrettable man to bury.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:29.50,0:16:32.63,Default,,0,0,0,,> Chief. I will take the first plane.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:32.63,0:16:39.60,Default,,0,0,0,,> Don't forget to have the commander on the first plane. I am the commander today. > Yeah...
Dialogue: 0,0:17:47.43,0:17:52.49,Default,,0,0,0,,> The first plane has Chief Yamamoto, Major General Takada, and Deputy Secretary Fukusaki.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:52.50,0:17:58.49,Default,,0,0,0,,Staff Officer Ugaki and Aviation Staff Officer Muroi are on board the second aircraft.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:02.46,0:18:11.87,Default,,0,0,0,,The Japanese forces called this Mitsubishi G4 "Hamaki(sigar)", and the US forces called it "Betty" or "Writer".
Dialogue: 0,0:18:12.60,0:18:21.74,Default,,0,0,0,,The equipment was made extremely light to extend its cruising range, which meant that it was flammable when shot.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:32.74,0:18:35.56,Default,,0,0,0,,> We lost one more. 16 aircraft left.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:36.05,0:18:43.87,Default,,0,0,0,,Whatever. If the enemy Yamato has a soul, there is also a Yankee soul here. Even so, I should meet Gentleman Yamamoto soon.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:51.08,0:18:54.84,Default,,0,0,0,,> Chief. 10 minutes before landing. > Oh. Really.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:54.84,0:18:57.67,Default,,0,0,0,,> Then Chief. It's time to prepare for landing,
Dialogue: 0,0:18:57.67,0:19:06.29,Default,,0,0,0,,> Are you ready? Should I laugh when I meet the soldiers for the first time? Or should I be dignified?
Dialogue: 0,0:19:28.01,0:19:29.98,Default,,0,0,0,,> I wonder if I came a little too early.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:40.81,0:19:44.56,Default,,0,0,0,,> That's it I'll use the radio.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:45.50,0:19:49.01,Default,,0,0,0,,Enemy plane found. 11 o'clock direction. Altitude 2000.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:49.01,0:19:53.67,Default,,0,0,0,,> Send to all aircraft. Discovered Betty. Drop the spare tank.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:59.87,0:20:06.25,Default,,0,0,0,,> It enemy aircraft. > Don't panic, the base is close.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:10.01,0:20:11.98,Default,,0,0,0,,> It is an enemy aircraft. > Damn.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:14.32,0:20:16.15,Default,,0,0,0,,> Protect the Chief.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:28.81,0:20:32.01,Default,,0,0,0,,> Which one is Yamamoto on? Anyway, I can shoot both.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:33.39,0:20:35.05,Default,,0,0,0,,It's the soul of Pearl Harbor.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:44.67,0:20:46.12,Default,,0,0,0,,> Are you okay?
Dialogue: 0,0:20:50.74,0:20:52.84,Default,,0,0,0,,> Recover!
Dialogue: 0,0:21:22.81,0:21:24.56,Default,,0,0,0,,> Betty
Dialogue: 0,0:21:31.67,0:21:34.67,Default,,0,0,0,,> I did it > Chief
Dialogue: 0,0:21:48.43,0:21:55.60,Default,,0,0,0,,> Chief, please hold on firmly. Chief.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:04.46,0:22:07.01,Default,,0,0,0,,> Don't lose sight of the Chief's plane. It was attacked.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:35.22,0:22:43.46,Default,,0,0,0,,> This is Mitchell. Message to all aircraft. Both Bettys fell. We have served our purpose. Run away if you want a medal.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:53.39,0:22:56.53,Default,,0,0,0,,> If I were on the first plane.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:57.29,0:23:09.32,Default,,0,0,0,,> When a man who tried to avoid the war ironically has to take command of the battle, he fights like a lion.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:10.36,0:23:14.67,Default,,0,0,0,,He probably knew his destiny,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:15.43,0:23:25.56,Default,,0,0,0,,lsoroku Yamamoto's death is by no means a careless death. By dying, he believed in those who followed him.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:26.46,0:23:33.94,Default,,0,0,0,,This sad act taught us that in order to win the battle, we must know our enemies well.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:34.67,0:23:41.84,Default,,0,0,0,,Even today, the more accurate information you have, the better you can make the decisions to win.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:42.77,0:23:51.15,Default,,0,0,0,,The death of Isoroku Yamamoto eventually led to the setting sun of the Japanese Empire.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:58.04,0:24:08.00,Default,,0,0,0,,The Pacific War taught us the preciousness of peace, but it also leaves us with many lessons to live.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:43.92,0:24:52.44,Default,,0,0,0,,If you are a man, test your strength It you are a man, burn your hope
Dialogue: 0,0:24:52.44,0:24:57.19,Default,,0,0,0,,If you area man, don't let yourself down
Dialogue: 0,0:24:57.20,0:25:13.50,Default,,0,0,0,,I and you are men and men bleed the same bright red blood.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:13.51,0:25:19.13,Default,,0,0,0,,Tatsunoko Production
